solutions.content:
**Explanation**
My first thought process was to build an O(N^2) solution, by creating all possible strings from A by swapping any two characters. However, I noticed that if I compare each position in two Buddy Strings A and B, then (N-2) positions will correspond, and exactly 2 will be unequal. If the 2 positions which have different characters in A and B be i and j respectively, then further we must have A[i] = B[j] & A[j] = B[i].

For eg. ABCDBA and ADCBBA. Here i = 1, j = 3. All the remaining indices are such that A[k] = B[k].

Also if we have two equal strings, then we won't have any indices i such that A[i] != B[i]. Two equal strings will be buddy strings, only if I have atleast one duplicate character, because I could then swap the duplicate characters.
For eg. ABCDBA and ABCDBA, we can swap (A, A) or (B, B).

```
class Solution {
public:
    bool buddyStrings(string A, string B) {
        if (A.length() != B.length()) {
            return false;
        }

		// Stores i  and j.
        vector<int> index;

		// To count for Duplicate Character.
        vector<int> freq(26, 0);

		// Stores whether Duplicate Character Exists.
        bool dup = false;

        for (int i=0; i<A.length(); ++i) {
			// Found the Duplicate. 
            if (++freq[A[i]-'a'] > 1) {
                dup = true;
            }

            if (A[i] != B[i]) {
                index.push_back(i);
				// More than 2 Different Characters.
                if (index.size() > 2)
                    return false;
            }
        }

        if (index.size() < 2) {
            if (index.size() == 1)
                return false;

            // 0 means identical, if i have duplicates, then True.
            return dup;
        }

        return (A[index[0]] == B[index[1]] && A[index[1]] == B[index[0]]);
    }
};
```

