# Intuition
The problem requires checking whether two strings can be made equal by swapping two characters. To solve this, we can iterate over the strings and compare the characters at each position. If we find two positions i and j such that s[i] != goal[i] and s[j] != goal[j], and s[i] == goal[j] and s[j] == goal[i], then it is possible to swap two letters to make the strings equal.

# Approach
1. Initialize an unordered map mp to store the characters of string s as keys and a stack of indices where each character occurs as values.
2. Initialize variables n and i to store the size of string s and initialize i as 0.
3. Iterate over the string s using a while loop until i reaches n.
4. If s[i] is not equal to goal[i], check if goal[i] exists in the map mp.
5. If it exists, swap s[i] with s[mp[goal[i]].top()] to perform the character swap.
6. Create a stack st and assign the stack of indices for the character goal[i] from the map mp.
7. While the stack st is not empty and s is still not equal to goal, perform the character swap by swapping s[i] with s[st.top()] and pop the top element of st.
8. Push the index i onto the stack for the character s[i] in the map mp.
9. Increment i by 1.
10. After the loop, check if s is equal to goal and the size of the map mp is less than n.
11. If both conditions are satisfied, return true; otherwise, return false.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: The while loop iterates over the string s, resulting in a time complexity of O(n), where n is the length of the string.
- Space complexity: The space complexity is O(n), where n is the length of the string s, as we are using a map to store the characters and their indices.


# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool buddyStrings(string s, string goal) {

        unordered_map<char,stack<int>> mp ;
        int n = s.size();
        int i=0;

        while(i<n){                
            if(s[i]!=goal[i]){
                if(mp.find(goal[i])!=mp.end()){
                    swap(s[i],s[mp[goal[i]].top()]);
                    stack<int> st = mp[goal[i]];
                    while(!st.empty() and s!=goal){
                        swap(s[i],s[st.top()]);
                        st.pop();
                    }
                }
            }
            mp[s[i]].push(i);
            i++;
        }
        if(s==goal and mp.size()<n) return true;
        return false;   
    }
};
```

